// Figure 6.2: Add to Cart Flow - Cross-MFE State Sharing
// Store MFE → API Gateway → Basket Service → Redis → Discount gRPC → Checkout MFE

// ==================== ACTORS ====================
Browser [icon: chrome, color: blue]
Store MFE [icon: shopping-bag, color: teal]
Host Shell [icon: home, color: green]
Router [icon: git-branch, color: orange]
API Gateway [icon: aws-api-gateway, color: red]
Basket Service [icon: shopping-cart, color: green]
Redis [icon: redis, color: red]
Discount Service [icon: tag, color: orange]
Checkout MFE [icon: shopping-cart, color: purple]

// ==================== PHASE 1: ADD TO CART ACTION ====================
// 1. User clicks "Add to Cart" from Store micro-frontend
Browser > Store MFE : Click "Add to Cart" button
Store MFE > Store MFE : Prepare addToCart request
// Payload: { productId, productName, price, quantity, imageFile }
Store MFE > API Gateway : POST /Basket/CreateBasket
// Request includes: UserName, Items array

// ==================== PHASE 2: SYNCHRONOUS API CHAIN ====================
// 2. Ocelot Gateway routes to Basket Service
API Gateway > API Gateway : Route to Basket Service
API Gateway > Basket Service : Forward to /api/v1/Basket/CreateBasket

// 2a. Basket Service queries Redis for existing cart
Basket Service > Redis : GET basket:{userName}
Redis > Basket Service : Return existing cart (or null)

// 2b. Basket Service calls Discount Service via gRPC
Basket Service > Discount Service : gRPC GetDiscount(productName)
// Low-latency call: <5ms
Discount Service > Basket Service : Return discount amount
// Response: { amount, description }

// 2c. Basket Service updates Redis with discounted prices
Basket Service > Basket Service : Merge item with discount
Basket Service > Basket Service : Calculate totals
Basket Service > Redis : SET basket:{userName}
// Store cart with: items, discounts, totalPrice
Redis > Basket Service : Cart saved successfully

// 2d. Response returns to Store micro-frontend
Basket Service > API Gateway : HTTP 200 OK (Cart response)
API Gateway > Store MFE : Cart data with discounts
Store MFE > Store MFE : Update cart icon count
Store MFE > Browser : Show "Added to cart" confirmation

// ==================== PHASE 3: NAVIGATION TO CART ====================
// 3. User navigates to /checkout, triggering host to load Checkout MFE
Browser > Host Shell : Navigate to /checkout
Host Shell > Router : Route analysis: /checkout
Router > Router : Match pattern /:appName/*
Router > Host Shell : Load Checkout MFE remote
Host Shell > Checkout MFE : Load remoteEntry.js
Checkout MFE > Host Shell : Module Federation injection
Host Shell > Checkout MFE : Mount Checkout application

// ==================== PHASE 4: CART DISPLAY ====================
// 4. Checkout micro-frontend fetches cart data and displays items
Checkout MFE > API Gateway : GET /Basket/GetBasket/{userName}
API Gateway > Basket Service : Forward to /api/v1/Basket/GetBasket/{userName}
Basket Service > Redis : GET basket:{userName}
Redis > Basket Service : Return cart data
// Cart includes: items with discounts, totalPrice, itemCount
Basket Service > API Gateway : HTTP 200 OK (Cart JSON)
API Gateway > Checkout MFE : Cart data response
Checkout MFE > Checkout MFE : Process cart items
Checkout MFE > Checkout MFE : Display items with applied discounts
Checkout MFE > Browser : Show shopping cart UI

// ==================== KEY COMPONENTS ====================
// Store: ProductCard.tsx (Add to Cart button)
// Store: useAddToCart hook (basket/hooks.ts)
// Store: Basket API (basket/apis.ts)
// Host: Cart state manager (cross-MFE communication)
// Backend: Ocelot Gateway (routing)
// Backend: Basket.API (Redis operations)
// Backend: Discount.API (gRPC server)
// Checkout: CartPreview.tsx (cart display)
// Checkout: useGetBasket hook (basket/hooks.ts)

// ==================== CROSS-MFE STATE SHARING ====================
// Cart state persists in Redis (Basket Service)
// Store MFE adds items → Checkout MFE displays items
// Shared state via backend API, not frontend storage
// Ensures consistency across independently deployed micro-frontends

